# Email Accessibility Standards

## Content Structure and Semantics
- Use proper HTML heading structure (h1, h2, h3) for content hierarchy
- Implement logical reading order that follows visual layout
- Create meaningful link text that describes destination
- Avoid relying solely on visual formatting for conveying meaning
- Use semantic markup for emphasis and importance
- Include proper language attributes on HTML elements

## Visual Design Considerations
- Maintain minimum 4.5:1 color contrast ratio for text content
- Avoid using color alone to convey important information
- Implement minimum 14px font size for body text
- Use readable fonts with adequate line spacing
- Design for users with color vision deficiencies
- Ensure content is readable without style sheets

## Image Accessibility
- Provide descriptive alt text for all informational images
- Use empty alt attributes for decorative images
- Include role="presentation" for purely decorative elements
- Avoid embedding critical text within images
- Ensure sufficient contrast for text overlaid on images
- Create meaningful captions for complex visual information

## Interactive Elements
- Ensure large, touch-friendly target areas for buttons and links
- Implement clear visual focus indicators for interactive elements
- Design for keyboard-only navigation where supported
- Provide explicit labels for form controls
- Group related form elements with appropriate markup
- Ensure sufficient color contrast for interactive elements

## Testing and Validation
- Test with screen reader technology
- Validate with color contrast analysis tools
- Verify readability in high-contrast mode
- Test functionality with keyboard-only navigation
- Validate template rendering across email clients
- Document accessibility compliance for each template

